Hi Werner,

Thanks for the bug report.

The code around the crash site has been significantly improved since the 2.3 series.  If you can, upgrading to a 2.4.* release should solve your problems (as well as making it easier for us to support you).

However in this case the bug seems pretty straightforward.  According to the backtrace from glib, imapd is crashing in free() called from search_free() which probably (modulo possible tail recursion optimisation by the compiler) means

// lib/charset.c
 627 void search_free(struct convert_rock *rock)
 628 {
 629     if (rock && rock->state) {
 630         struct search_state *s = (struct search_state *)rock->state;
 631         if (s->starts) free(s->starts);               <----
 632     }
 633     basic_free(rock);
 634 }

where s->starts is declared thus

  96 struct search_state {
  97     size_t *starts;

and allocated thus

 714 struct convert_rock *search_init(const char *substr, comp_pat *pat) {
...
 726     s->starts = xmalloc(s->max_start * sizeof(int));

I see from the memory map that your machine is a 64 bit machine.  On such a machine, sizeof(int) == 4 and sizeof(size_t) == 8 so the allocation for s->starts will be half the size needed.  Normal use of s->starts will thus run off the end of the allocation and probably trash the heap management structures, confusing the later free().  This should be fixable with a trivial patch.
